â“ï¸Q3)Your microservices are running on AWS ECS. Randomly, some API calls fail with 502 Bad Gateway. There are no clear error logs. How do you debug this?

âœ…ï¸Solution:

ğŸ”¹ï¸Monitor API latency and service health metrics (New Relic, Prometheus).

ğŸ”¹ï¸Check load balancer logs for connection timeouts or container crashes.

ğŸ”¹ï¸Implement retry mechanisms on transient failures.

http:
 retries:
 attempts: 3
 perTryTimeout: 2s

ğŸ”¹ Key Concepts: AWS ECS, Load Balancer Debugging, Logging, New Relic.


â“ï¸Q4)Your system receives millions of read requests per second. Database reads are slowing down. How do you optimize it?

âœ…ï¸Solution:

ğŸ”¹ï¸Implement CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation).

ğŸ”¹ï¸Use a Read Replica Database or ElasticSearch for queries.

ğŸŒ´Example:
ğŸ‘‡
@Query("SELECT * FROM product_read WHERE category = ?1")
List<Product> findByCategory(String category);

ğŸ”¹ Key Concepts: CQRS, Read Replicas, ElasticSearch, NoSQL.

â“ï¸Q5)Your Order Service emits an order_created event. The Payment Service and Inventory Service consume this event asynchronously. How do you ensure they process the event exactly once?

âœ…ï¸Solution:

ğŸ”¹ï¸Implement Event Sourcing (Kafka, Debezium).

ğŸ”¹ï¸Use Idempotency Keys to prevent duplicate processing.

ğŸ”¹ï¸Maintain Event Logs for Retry.

ğŸŒ´Example:
ğŸ‘‡
@KafkaListener(topics = "order_created")
public void processEvent(String message) {
 if (!isDuplicate(message)) {
 saveEvent(message);
 }
}

ğŸ”¹ Key Concepts: Event Sourcing, Kafka, Exactly-Once Semantics.


